initial_story: bias triangles represent features in stability diagrams of quantum dot (qd)devices, whose occurrence and property analysis are crucial indicators for spinphysics. nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and availability ofdata as well as the subtlety of physical phenomena of interest have hindered anautomatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) onhuman labelling and verification. we introduce a feature extraction frameworkfor bias triangles, built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer visionmethods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification ofphysical properties of the former. thereby, the need for human input or largetraining datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is circumvented,while additionally enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and featurelabeling. in particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (psb)detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any trainingdata as a direct result of this approach.
stories: In stability diagrams of quantum dot devices, bias triangles signify key features, and analyzing their occurrence and properties is essential for spin physics research. However, the limited availability and quality of data, as well as the complexity of the underlying physical phenomena, have hindered the development of an automated and tailored analysis framework, often requiring human intervention and verification. We propose a feature extraction framework for bias triangles, leveraging unsupervised computer vision techniques based on segmentation, which enables the direct identification and quantification of physical properties. This approach eliminates the need for human input or large training datasets required for supervised learning methods, and also facilitates the automation of pixel-wise shape and feature labeling. Notably, our framework enables effective and efficient detection of Pauli spin blockade without relying on any training data.

In the study of quantum dot devices, bias triangles are crucial indicators, and examining their presence and characteristics is vital for advancing spin physics research. Nevertheless, the scarcity and poor quality of data, combined with the intricacy of the underlying physical mechanisms, have impeded the creation of a tailored and automated analytical tool, frequently necessitating human involvement and verification. We introduce a novel framework for extracting features from bias triangles, harnessing unsupervised computer vision techniques rooted in segmentation, which permits the direct recognition and quantification of physical properties. This approach obviates the need for human input or extensive training datasets required for supervised learning methods, and also enables the automation of pixel-level shape and feature labeling. Significantly, our framework facilitates the efficient and effective detection of Pauli spin blockade without relying on any prior training data.
